<subSubSection pageId="60" pageNumber="61" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="60.[151,1436,703,1521]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,775,800]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Description.</emphasis>
Branching sponge with coalescent tubes, rising from a common base (
<figureCitation box="[1132,1236,775,800]" captionStart="FIGURE 26" captionStartId="61.[151,250,1979,2001]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,409,1957]" captionTargetId="figure@61.[151,1435,409,1957]" captionTargetPageId="61" captionText="FIGURE 26. Callyspongia (Cladochalina) diffusa (Ridley, 1884). A. In situ; B &amp; C. Skeletal architecture (B, x5; C, x10); D. Oxeas." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2651502/files/figure.png" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Fig. 26A</figureCitation>
). Surface smooth, finely hispid with numerous oscules, 
<quantity box="[569,633,812,836]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" unit="mm" value="1.0">1 mm</quantity>
in diameter, evenly scattered on the surface of the sponge. Texture firm but spongy, velvety to the touch, compressible. Colour in life pale pink-white; in preservative, white.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="60.[151,1436,703,1521]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,302,884,909]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Skeleton</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[320,458,884,909]" captionStart="FIGURE 26" captionStartId="61.[151,250,1979,2001]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,409,1957]" captionTargetId="figure@61.[151,1435,409,1957]" captionTargetPageId="61" captionText="FIGURE 26. Callyspongia (Cladochalina) diffusa (Ridley, 1884). A. In situ; B &amp; C. Skeletal architecture (B, x5; C, x10); D. Oxeas." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2651502/files/figure.png" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Fig. 26B, C</figureCitation>
). Choanosomal skeleton is a regular network of rectangular meshes, 
<quantity box="[1260,1405,884,909]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.925" metricValueMax="3.45" metricValueMin="2.4" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" unit="mm" value="292.5" valueMax="345.0" valueMin="240.0">240–345 µm</quantity>
in diameter, formed by primary multispicular fibres, 123 (67–96) µm thick, which are connected perpendicularly by multispicular secondary fibres and showing no fasciculation. Spongin is sparsely scattered in the choanosome, but the multispicular fibres are covered with sponging sheath. The ectosomal skeleton is a plumoreticulation of protruding spicules and is an extension of the primary spiculation formed within the choanosome.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="60.[151,1436,703,1521]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,456,1063,1088]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Spicules. Megascleres</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[471,576,1063,1088]" captionStart="FIGURE 26" captionStartId="61.[151,250,1979,2001]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,409,1957]" captionTargetId="figure@61.[151,1435,409,1957]" captionTargetPageId="61" captionText="FIGURE 26. Callyspongia (Cladochalina) diffusa (Ridley, 1884). A. In situ; B &amp; C. Skeletal architecture (B, x5; C, x10); D. Oxeas." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2651502/files/figure.png" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Fig. 26D</figureCitation>
). Oxeas, smooth, curved and sharply pointed, 107 (101–113) × 5 (5–7) µm, n = 10.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="60.[151,1436,703,1521]" box="[199,1198,1135,1160]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,644,1135,1160]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Substratum, depth range and ecology</emphasis>
. Found growing on coral spp. at a depth of 
<specimenCount box="[1134,1198,1136,1160]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" type="generic">
<quantity box="[1134,1194,1136,1160]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" unit="m" value="30.0">30 m</quantity>
.
</specimenCount>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="60.[151,1436,703,1521]" box="[199,957,1172,1197]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,495,1172,1197]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Geographic distribution.</emphasis>
Sodwana Bay, east coast of 
<collectingCountry box="[814,957,1172,1197]" name="South Africa" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">South Africa</collectingCountry>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="60" pageNumber="61" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="60.[151,1436,703,1521]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1207,1232]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="(Ridley, 1884)" authorityName="Ridley" authorityYear="1884" baseAuthorityName="Ridley" baseAuthorityYear="1884" box="[322,901,1207,1232]" class="Demospongiae" family="Callyspongiidae" genus="Callyspongia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="diffusa" subGenus="Cladochalina">
<emphasis box="[322,732,1207,1232]" italics="true" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Callyspongia (Cladochalina) diffusa</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Ridley" box="[747,892,1207,1232]" firstAuthor="Ridley" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" pagination="366 - 482" refId="ref48144" refString="Ridley, S. O. (1884) Spongiida. In: Report on the Zoological Collections made in the Indo-Pacific Ocean during the Voyage of H. M. S. Alert 1881 - 2. British Museum (Natural History), London. Istituti Biologici della Universita di Genova, 58 - 59, 69 - 75, pp. 366 - 482 + 582 - 635." type="journal article" year="1884">Ridley, 1884</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
is a widely distributed Indo-Pacific species and has been recorded from the Gulf of Manaar (
<bibRefCitation author="Dendy" box="[685,833,1244,1269]" firstAuthor="Dendy" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" pagination="73 - 99" refId="ref43066" refString="Dendy, A. (1889) Report on a second collection of sponges from the Gulf of Manaar. Annals and Magazine of Natural History, Series 6, 3, 73 - 99, pls. III-V. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222938909460303" type="journal article" year="1889">Dendy 1889</bibRefCitation>
), East African Coral coast (
<bibRefCitation author="Burton" box="[1163,1310,1244,1269]" firstAuthor="Burton" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" pagination="151 - 281" refId="ref41856" refString="Burton, M. (1959) Sponges. In: Scientific Reports. John Murray Expedition 1933 - 34, 10 (5). British Museum (Natural History), London, pp. 151 - 281." type="book chapter" year="1959">Burton 1959</bibRefCitation>
) and from 
<collectingCountry box="[151,299,1279,1304]" name="Mozambique" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Mozambique</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Thomas, P. A." box="[313,472,1279,1304]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" pagination="10 - 16" refId="ref51663" refString="Thomas, P. A. (1979 a) Demospongiae of Minicoy Island (Indian Ocean) Part 1 - orders Keratosida and Haplosclerida. Journal of the Marine Biological Association of India, 21 (1 - 2), 10 - 16." type="journal article" year="1979">Thomas 1979</bibRefCitation>
). This sponge is easily identified by its unique morphology. Our specimen agrees well with the original published description of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Ridley" baseAuthorityYear="1884" box="[622,1033,1316,1341]" class="Demospongiae" family="Callyspongiidae" genus="Callyspongia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="diffusa" subGenus="Cladochalina">
<emphasis box="[622,1033,1316,1341]" italics="true" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Callyspongia (Cladochalina) diffusa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[1101,1214,1316,1341]" name="Singapore" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Singapore</collectingCountry>
and the subsequent description of material from 
<collectingCountry box="[473,621,1351,1376]" name="Mozambique" pageId="60" pageNumber="61">Mozambique</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Thomas, P. A." box="[635,794,1351,1376]" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" pagination="10 - 16" refId="ref51663" refString="Thomas, P. A. (1979 a) Demospongiae of Minicoy Island (Indian Ocean) Part 1 - orders Keratosida and Haplosclerida. Journal of the Marine Biological Association of India, 21 (1 - 2), 10 - 16." type="journal article" year="1979">Thomas 1979</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
